  "signature": "ed25519:b4e2d1f3a5c7e9b1d3f5a7c9e1b3d5f7a9c1e3b5d7f9a1c3e5b7d9f1a3c5e7b9",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "SQA level 2 requires documented version control, build reproducibility records, and regression test suite covering all QoI extraction routines. Achieved level 3 additionally includes independent code review and formal change-control procedures per FDA software guidance.",
      "rationale": "The FEA ensemble (Ansys Mechanical 2021R2, in-house FDA Python post-processing scripts) is managed under Git version control with tagged releases. A regression test suite of 47 benchmark problems was executed at each release. Independent peer review of the post-processing scripts was completed by a second analyst. All three FEA platforms produced consistent stiffness and force outputs within 0.5% on a standard cantilever beam benchmark."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 2 requires verification against at least one analytical solution or published benchmark for each element type used in the model. Patch test passage and documented convergence behavior are required.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical SOLID186 and CONTA174 elements were verified against Hertzian contact analytical solutions and NAFEMS benchmark LE10. Patch tests passed for all element formulations. Documented in verification report VR-2021-001."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 2 requires a formal mesh convergence study demonstrating that QoI changes less than 5% between the penultimate and final mesh refinement levels, with at least three mesh densities evaluated.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh convergence study was conducted on the pedicle screw shank and rod interface regions. Construct stiffness changed by 1.8% between medium and fine meshes; yield force changed by 2.3%. The fine mesh (approximately 420,000 elements) was selected for all production runs. Element quality metrics (Jacobian ratio, aspect ratio) were within Ansys recommended bounds."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 1 requires confirmation that solver residuals converge to manufacturer-default tolerances and that no solver warnings were issued for the production runs.",
      "rationale": "All nonlinear static analyses converged within 15 substeps with force residuals below 1e-4. No solver warnings or unconverged substeps were recorded across the 11 construct simulations. Sparse direct solver (SPARSE) was used; iterative solver was evaluated and produced results within 0.1% for all QoIs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 2 requires a documented simulation protocol reviewed by a qualified second analyst, with evidence that boundary conditions, material assignments, and load application were independently verified prior to each production run.",
      "rationale": "A written simulation protocol (SP-2021-NC-001) was prepared and independently reviewed by a senior biomechanical engineer not involved in model construction. Boundary conditions replicating the ASTM F1717 fixture geometry were verified against fixture engineering drawings. Material property assignments were cross-checked against the material input log by the reviewer."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "The model form — linear-elastic titanium alloy with bilinear isotropic hardening for post-yield behavior, frictional contact at screw-rod interface (mu=0.2), rigid UHMWPE block representation — was judged appropriate for the compression-bending regime. Published literature (Nagaraja 2019, Goel 2006) supports the use of bilinear hardening for Ti-6Al-4V in quasi-static bending. Sensitivity of QoIs to friction coefficient was evaluated over mu=0.1–0.3; stiffness varied by less than 3%, yield force by less than 4%. The required level of 3 reflects the MEDIUM model risk and the importance of contact representation to the failure mode; however, the structured acceptance criteria record for this factor was not separately filed at the time of assessment — the rationale above captures the engineering judgment applied."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 2 requires that all material properties and geometric inputs are traceable to primary sources (material certificates, CMM reports) and that uncertainty in key inputs is quantified. Level 3 additionally requires a formal sensitivity analysis mapping input uncertainty to QoI uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V elastic modulus (114 GPa) and yield strength (880 MPa) were sourced from lot-specific material certificates for the screw batch used in testing. Geometric dimensions were taken from CMM inspection reports for each of the 11 constructs. A one-at-a-time sensitivity analysis varied E ±5% and yield strength ±8%; construct stiffness varied ±4.7% and yield force ±6.1%, consistent with experimental scatter."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 2 requires that test samples are drawn from the same design family and manufacturing process as the device to be cleared, with documented traceability of lot numbers and dimensional inspection.",
      "rationale": "All 11 constructs used production-representative 7.5 mm non-cannulated pedicle screws from lot NC-2020-07, verified by dimensional inspection (CMM) against drawing tolerances. Two independent laboratories (FDA OSEL and DePuy Synthes) each tested a subset of constructs under blinded conditions. Sample traceability documented in test report TR-2021-F1717-NC."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 2 requires that testing spans at least two distinct loading rates or environmental conditions representative of the COU envelope, with documented rationale for the conditions selected. Level 1 is acceptable only when a single condition is used and a documented justification is provided that the single condition bounds the clinical use scenario.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted at a single crosshead displacement rate of 5 mm/min per ASTM F1717. A second loading rate was not evaluated due to resource constraints. The achieved level of 1 falls below the required level of 2; this gap is acknowledged and mitigated by the observation that ASTM F1717 is a standardized quasi-static protocol and rate sensitivity for Ti-6Al-4V in this regime is negligible per published literature. A formal rate-sensitivity study is recommended for future submissions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 2 requires documented comparison of all simulation input parameters (geometry, material properties, boundary conditions) to the corresponding experimental conditions, with quantified differences and justification that discrepancies do not materially affect QoI predictions.",
      "rationale": "A parameter equivalency table was prepared mapping each FEA input to the corresponding experimental measurement. Maximum geometric discrepancy between nominal FEA geometry and CMM-measured construct dimensions was 0.12 mm (screw shank diameter). Sensitivity analysis confirmed that a 0.12 mm diameter change produces less than 1% change in stiffness. Fixture compliance was measured experimentally and incorporated into the FEA boundary conditions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 3 requires that QoI predictions are compared to experimental results using both a relative error metric (<10% mean error) and a normalized validation metric (E/uval < 1.96), with results reported for each QoI individually and for the ensemble.",
      "rationale": "For construct stiffness: mean FEA error = 4.2%, E/uval = 0.87. For yield force: mean FEA error = 6.8%, E/uval = 1.43. For force at 40 mm: mean FEA error = 5.1%, E/uval = 1.12. All three QoIs satisfy both acceptance metrics. Inter-laboratory variability (coefficient of variation 3.1–5.6%) was within expected bounds for ASTM F1717."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 2 requires that each QoI is directly linked to a clinical or regulatory endpoint with documented justification. Level 3 additionally requires a quantitative argument (e.g., safety factor analysis) connecting QoI thresholds to patient safety margins.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three QoIs specified in ASTM F1717 and directly referenced in FDA guidance for pedicle screw 510(k) submissions. A safety factor analysis demonstrated that the predicted yield force (mean 2,847 N) exceeds the estimated in vivo peak compressive load at the instrumented level (approximately 1,200 N) by a factor of 2.37, providing quantitative confidence in the safety margin."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 3 requires that the validation scenario matches the COU geometry, loading mode, and device configuration, and that a documented argument addresses any differences between the validation scenario and the intended clinical use environment.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity directly replicates the COU: ASTM F1717 compression-bending of the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw construct, identical fixture geometry, identical loading direction. The primary difference between the bench test and the clinical environment is the absence of bone and soft tissue in the bench model; this is conservative for structural assessment as bone provides additional constraint. The FEA model similarly omits bone, maintaining consistency between simulation and experiment."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-decision-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "Twelve of thirteen V&V 40 credibility factors meet or exceed their required levels. The single shortfall — Test conditions achieving level 1 against a required level of 2 — is mitigated by the quasi-static nature of the ASTM F1717 protocol and published evidence of negligible rate sensitivity for Ti-6Al-4V in this loading regime. All three QoIs satisfy both the relative error (<10%) and normalized validation metric (E/uval < 1.96) acceptance bounds. The overall credibility package is judged sufficient to support a Medium assurance level conclusion and regulatory submission for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw design.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
